  "text": "We have assumed that L min j n j , or in the asymptotic sense, L = o(n), for the purposes of (1) η jk P → η jk as n → ∞ and n j /n → ρ j for 0 < ρ j < 1, j = 1, . . . , J, and (2) the sample covariance or correlation matrices are invertable and thus the test statistics are continuous functions of the η jk 's under the null. These conditions are needed, together with the moment assumptions (a)-(d), for the test statistics as functions of the η jk 's and those as functions of bootstrap samples of η jk 's to converge to the same distribution. When L min j n j does not hold, the sample covariance may be ill-conditioned and not invertable. A possible remedy is to use shrinkage estimators, for example, the optimal linear shrinkage estimator proposed by [CITATION_1] . In our case, the optimal linear coefficients for weighting the sample covariance and the identity matrix may be estimated using V for the H-D bootstrap or V j for the H-I bootstrap, and be treated as fixed during the resampling. This linear shrinkage estimator is a consistent estimator for covariance even if L = O(n). Further study is needed to evaluate the performance of this practice.",
